74":"1474","about 1474":"circa 1474","1549":"1549","West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England":"West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1452–":"1452–Deceased","1452–Male":"1452–Deceased","1453–Female":"1453–Deceased","1474–1552":"1474–1552","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1430–1478":"1430–1478","1558":"1558","1426":"1426","1502":"1502","ABT 1472":"about 1472","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1552":"1552","1453":"1453","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1474":"1474","about 1474":"about 1474","1549":"1549","West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England":"West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Freebody","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English  <i>fre</i> ‘free’ +  <i>bodi</i> ‘body, physique; person, individual’ (Old English  <i>frēo</i>,  <i>frīo</i> +  <i>bodig</i>), used of a ‘free man’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":3,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":97,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":106,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Freebody was born in 1452, in West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England, his father, Sir William Freebody, was 26 and his mother, Lady Katherine Savage, was 22. He married Mrs. Richard Freebody about 1472, in West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1452–":"1452–Surnud","1452–Male":"1452–Surnud","1453–Female":"1453–Surnud","1474–1552":"1474–1552","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1430–1478":"1430–1478","1558":"1558","1426":"1426","1502":"1502","ABT 1472":"umbes 1472","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1552":"1552","1453":"1453","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1474":"1474","about 1474":"umbes 1474","1549":"1549","West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England":"West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"1452–":"1452–Kuollut","1452–Male":"1452–Kuollut","1453–Female":"1453–Kuollut","1474–1552":"1474–1552","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1430–1478":"1430–1478","1558":"1558","1426":"1426","1502":"1502","ABT 1472":"noin 1472","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1552":"1552","1453":"1453","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1474":"1474","about 1474":"noin 1474","1549":"1549","West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England":"West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England"},"fr":{"1452–":"1452–Décédé","1452–Male":"1452–Décédé","1453–Female":"1453–Décédée","1474–1552":"1474–1552","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1430–1478":"1430–1478","1558":"1558","1426":"1426","1502":"1502","ABT 1472":"environ 1472","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1552":"1552","1453":"1453","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1474":"1474","about 1474":"environ 1474","1549":"1549","West Bromwich, Staffordshire, England":"West Bromwich, Staffordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard Freebody est né en 1452, à West Bromwich, Staffordshire, Angleterre, son père, Sir William Freebody, avait 26 ans et sa mère, Lady Katherine Savage, avait 22 ans. Il a épousé Mrs. Richard Freebody environ 1472, à West Bromwich, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"14